,"Relaxation phase with closed valves","Atrial contraction phase","Isovolumetric contraction phase with closed valves"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe initial phase of systole is characterized by \u003Cstrong\u003Eisovolumetric contraction phase with closed valves\u003C/strong\u003E. During this period, ventricular pressure rises while chamber volume remains unchanged because all valves are closed. This continues until ventricular pressure exceeds arterial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive ventricular filling phase\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during early diastole when blood flows from atria to ventricles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEjection phase with semilunar valves open\u003C/strong\u003E follows the isovolumetric contraction phase once pressure is sufficient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelaxation phase with closed valves\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at the beginning of diastole as the ventricles relax\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial contraction phase\u003C/strong\u003E represents the final phase of diastole, not the start of systole\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis initial phase of systole is marked by the first heart sound (S1) which occurs when rising ventricular pressure causes the atrioventricular valves to snap shut.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ventricular systole begins with a phase where pressure increases but volume remains constant as all valves are closed","The closure of atrioventricular valves creates the first heart sound and marks the start of systole"],"references":["Boron WF, Boulpaep EL. Medical physiology. 3rd ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:30:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:31:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9574"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68692"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4903"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cardiac physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-13T22:30:50+10:30","updatedAt"